properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An upper disturbance moving through central Manitoba today will bring an additional swath of snow at times heavy. General amounts across central Manitoba will see 5 to 10 cm today with another 2 to 4 cm tonight for storm totals around 15 to 25 cm. The largest snowfall area is expected to be in a narrow band between The Pas and Swan River, east through the Lake Manitoba north basin. To the south, the accompanying cold front will move through southern portions of the province this morning bringing flurries with a risk of freezing rain and freezing drizzle. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system will bring significant amounts of rain beginning Monday evening through Tuesday evening over Southern and Central Quebec. Further north, snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres are possible from Monday morning to Tuesday evening in a corridor stretching from Abitibi towards Chaleur Bay, including Quebec City. Snow accompanied by moderate winds may reduce visibilities locally in blowing snow. Freezing rain is likely in the vicinity of the snow-to-rain transition area. A more important episode of freezing rain is also likely for areas of the St. Lawrence Valley between Montreal and Quebec City. Travel could be difficult, especially at rush hour Tuesday morning. There is still much uncertainty about the track of this system and thus about the type and amount of precipitation expected. Please stay tuned for future forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snow and freezing rain likely for Tuesday. Total snowfall: 10-25 cm. Locations: Most of New Brunswick except for the Fundy coast. Time span: Tuesday morning to Wednesday morning. Remarks: A low pressure system is expected to slide into New Brunswick from southern Quebec on Tuesday and move southeast over Nova Scotia on Wednesday. Snowfall is expected to begin over central and northern New Brunswick around midnight Tuesday and continue into Wednesday morning. A prolonged period of freezing rain is possible for parts of southern and central New Brunswick with rain expected further south over the Fundy region. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Maximum wind gusts: northerly 70 km/h. Time span: until early this afternoon Remarks: Fresh snow will combine with strong northerly winds to produce reduced visibility in blowing snow. Conditions are forecast to improve by this afternoon as the snow tapers off and the winds ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds and fresh snow are creating near zero visibilities in blowing snow. Blizzard conditions are occurring in Iqaluit as a deep low pressure system over Frobisher Bay moves eastward. Very strong northwest winds gusting to 90 km/h will are expected to develop today. The blizzard will continue today and tonight. While the winds will subside a bit for Monday, blowing snow will continue. Near blizzard conditions will likely persist for most of Monday. Wind chill values are also expected to fall to near -48 during the blizzard. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
